'''Tumkur Sunandamma''' ({{lang-kn|ಟಿ. ಸುನಂದಮ್ಮ}}, born [[Tumkur]], 1917 &ndash; died [[Bangalore]], 27 January 2006) was an Indian writer and humorist in the [[Kannada]] language. She was a recipient of the Karnataka Sahitya Akademi Award.
==Early life== Sunandamma was born in Tumkur, Mysore in 1917.<ref name=Lal1992/> She belonged to a distinguished family of the [[Kingdom of Mysore]], her father T. Ramaiah being a senior civil servant.<ref name=hinduobit>{{cite news|newspaper=The Hindu|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/t-sunandamma-is-dead/article3246507.ece|title=T. Sunandamma is dead|date=January 29, 2006}}</ref>
Despite social strictures against the education of girls at the time, she studied up to high school. The lone girl in her class, she outperformed the boys, leading to considerable pressure from their parents to have her removed from the school. She was married off at the age of 11.<ref name=hindu2006>{{cite news|newspaper=The Hindu|title=Grandmom of laughter|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-fridayreview/article3217066.ece|author=Bageshree S.|date=February 3, 2006}}</ref>
==Career== Sunandamma began writing poetry for a children's magazine, ''Makkala pustaka'', while still a child. At the age of 25, her articles began to appear in the newly established humour magazine ''Koravanji'', receiving critical praise.<ref name="Lal1992">{{cite book|editor=Mohan Lal|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: Sasay to Zorgot|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnPoYxrRfc0C&pg=PA4224|volume=V|year=1992|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1221-3|page=4224}}</ref><ref name=hindu2006/>
When she moved to [[Bangalore]], her observations of the middle-class lives of her neighbours, in particular the women of [[Basavangudi]], began to inform her writings.<ref name="Joseph2003">{{cite book|author=Ammu Joseph|title=Storylines: Conversations with Women Writers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1t1jAAAAMAAJ|year=2003|publisher=Women's World India and Asmita Resource Centre for Women|page=274}}</ref> They were lauded as ''potent and pungent''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Illustrated Weekly of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O3Y6AQAAIAAJ|volume=102|date=October 1981|publisher=Bennett, Coleman & Company|page=37|number=4}}</ref>
Sunandamma wrote radio plays for [[All India Radio]].<ref name=hinduobit/> Several of her works were adapted by others for the theatre. ''All's well'', an English reworking from a Kannada play by Sundar based on Sunandamma's short story ''Aadaddella Olithe…?'' was directed Pramod Shiggaon and presented in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Mid-Day|url=http://archive.mid-day.com/news/2008/oct/061008-alls-well-comedy-plays-ranga-shankara-theatre-reviews.htm|title=A happy couple and time pass|author=|date=October 6, 2008}}</ref> ''Heegadre hege?'' written by K. Y. Narayana Swamy and directed by Pramod Shiggaon, was performed in Bangalore in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/199544/in-brief.html|newspaper=Deccan Herald|title=In Brief: Kannada play|date=October 21, 2011}}</ref>
==Honours== In 1979, Sunandamma was elected the first president of the Karnataka Lekhakiyara Sangha (Karnataka Women Writers' Association).<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Bangalore Mirror|url=http://www.bangaloremirror.com/entertainment/lounge/Sangha-for-the-women-writers/articleshow/25451931.cms|date=November 8, 2013|author=Prathibha Nandakumar|title=Sangha for the women writers}}</ref> She received the [[Karnataka Sahitya Academy Award]] in 1981.<ref name=Lal1992/> In 2004, she was awarded the Anupama Prasasti, a literary award from the Karnataka Women Writers' Association.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Times of India|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Sunandamma-bags-award/articleshow/679449.cms|title=Sunandamma bags award|date=May 17, 2004}}</ref>
==Selected works== * ''Jambhada cheela'' * ''Bannada chitte'' * ''Pepparamentu'' * ''Muttina chenda'' * ''Raddi gadi'' * ''Vriksha vahana'' * ''Nanna attegiri'' * ''Dr M. Shivaram'' &ndash; a biography * ''Tenali Ramakrishnan'' &ndash; a children's biography * ''Samaya Sindu'' * {{cite book|title=Kanyamanigalige Kanthupithana Daye|isbn= 978-81728-6577-1}} * {{cite book|title=Best of Sunandamma|editor=Y. N. Gundu Rao|publisher=Ankita|date=2006}}
