{{Infobox language |name=Tanema |nativename = ''Tetawo'' |states=[[Solomon Islands]] |region=[[Vanikoro]] |speakers=1 |date=2012 |ref=<ref name="francois" /> |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Temotu languages|Temotu]] |fam5=[[Utupua–Vanikoro languages|Utupua–Vanikoro]] |fam6=[[Vanikoro languages|Vanikoro]] |iso3=tnx |glotto=tane1237 |glottorefname=Tanema }}
'''Tanema''' (Tetawo, Tetau) is a nearly extinct language of the island of [[Vanikoro]] in the easternmost province of the [[Solomon Islands]]. As of 2012, it is only spoken by one speaker, Lainol Nalo.<ref name=francois>[http://alex.francois.free.fr/AF-field.htm#Solomons Homepage of the linguist A. François] ([[LACITO]]-[[CNRS]]).</ref><ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/south-pacific-islands-threatened-by-more-than-just-rising-sea-levels-a-838675-2.html “The Mystery of the Sinking South Pacific Islands” — Part 2: A Language's Lone Survivor] (article in [[Der Spiegel]], 15/06/2012).</ref> It has been [[language shift|replaced]] by [[Teanu language|Teanu]], the main language of Vanikoro.
Some information on Tanema, as well as on the two other languages of the island, can be found in {{Harvcoltxt|François|2009}}.
