{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}} {{About|the poet|the place|Ulloor}} {{Infobox writer |name = Ulloor S. Parameswara Iyer |image = Ulloor.jpeg |imagesize = |caption = |pseudonym = |birth_date = {{birth date|1877|06|06|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Changanassery]], [[Kerala]] |death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1949|6|15|1877|06|06}} |deathplace = |occupation = Poet |nationality = Indian |period = |genre = |subject = |movement = |debutworks = |influences = |influenced = |signature = |website = |footnotes = |notableworks =''Umakeralam'', ''Karnabhushanam'', ''Pingala'', ''Kerala Sahitya Charithram'' }}
'''Ulloor S. Parameswara Iyer''' (18 June 1877 – 15 June 1949) (commonly known as ''' Ulloor''') was a [[Malayalam]] poet and historian. He was one of the [[triumvirate poets of modern Malayalam|triumvirate poets of]] [[Kerala]] in the first half of the 20th century, along with [[Kumaran Asan]] and [[Vallathol Narayana Menon]].<ref>{{cite book|title=This Ancient Lyre: Selected Poems|year=2005|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=8126017910|page=10|author=O. N. V. Kurup|editor=A. J. Thomas}}</ref>
Ulloor was born at the Thamarassery Illam at [[Perunna]], [[Changanassery]].<ref name=Yentha/> Since his ancestral home was at [[Ulloor]], he came to be known as ''Ulloor'' S. Parameswara Iyer.<ref name=Yentha>{{cite web|title=Statues Of Trivandrum: Mahakavi Ulloor S Parameswara Iyer|url=http://www.yentha.com/news/view/4/statues-of-trivandrum-mahakavi-ulloor-s-parameswara-iyer|website=Yentha.com|author=Mukesh|date=16 May 2012|accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref> His father died when he was young and his mother raised him.<ref name=Yentha/> He graduated with [[Latin honors|Honors]] in [[Philosophy]] from Maharajas College and joined the Travancore State Services.<ref name=Yentha/> Later he took Degree in Law and [[Master's]] in [[Malayalam]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]].<ref name=Yentha/> He was later appointed as the income tax officer and then as the Chief Secretary.<ref name=Yentha/>
Ulloor published his [[mahakavya]] ''Umakeralam'' in 1914. Until then, only [[Pandalam Kerala Varma]]'s ''Rukmamgadacharitham'' was considered as a complete mahakavya in Malayalam.<ref>{{cite book|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature|year=1988|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=8126011947|page=1185}}</ref> Poet [[K. Ayyappa Paniker]] has noted that ''Umakeralam'' is a "work of great devotion: devotion to the land, to the language, to a poetic tradition" Ulloor, like his contemporaries [[Kumaran Asan]] and [[Vallathol Narayana Menon]], also wrote a number of short narratives or ''khandakavyas'', of which the most famous are ''Karnabhooshanam'' and ''Pingala''. In the former he celebrates [[Karna]]'s infinite generosity and dedication to principles. In the latter he tries to portray the transformation of a courtesan overnight into a pious and refined character - almost a saint. Some of his other best known works were ''Bhakthideepika'', and ''Chithrasala''.<ref name=Yentha/> Uloor also wrote quite a large number of lyrics and shorter pieces, now available in various collections.
After Ulloor's death, the [[University of Kerala]] published one of his most noted works ''Kerala Sahitya Charithram'', which describes the history of Malayalam language, culture, and literature.<ref name=Yentha/> He studied ancient literature and palm leaf manuscripts to bring out old literary works such as ''Rama Charitham'' poem and ''Doothavakyam'' prose.<ref name=Yentha/>
==Legacy== The [[India Posts|Indian Posts and Telegraph]] department released a [[commemorative stamp]] after Ulloor's death.<ref name=Yentha /> A full size statue of Ulloor was unveiled by the [[President of India|Indian President]] [[Neelam Sanjeeva Reddy]] in [[Thiruvananthapuram]] on 15 May 1981.<ref name=Yentha/>
